            <ab>
                <lb n="1" style="text-direction:r-to-l"/><persName key="Χαιρεδέμος">Χαιρεδέμο</persName> τόδε σε͂μα πατὲρ ἔστε<supplied reason="lost"
                        >σε</supplied>
                <lb n="2" style="text-direction:l-to-r"/><supplied reason="lost">θ</supplied>ανόντος 
                <persName><name key="Ἀνφιχάρες">Ἀνφιχάρ<supplied reason="omitted">ε</supplied>ς</name></persName> ἀγαθὸν παῖδα ὀ 
                <lb n="3" style="text-direction:r-to-l" break="no"/><supplied reason="omitted">λ</supplied>οφυρόμενο̣<supplied reason="lost">ς</supplied>. <persName><name key="Φαίδιμος">Φαίδιμος</name></persName> ἐποίε.</ab></div>
            
            <div type="translation">
                <p>Amphichares, father of the late Chairedemus, set this marker, lamenting a good son.
                    Phaedimus made (this).</p></div>

            <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription is reported to have been found in Athens. The paleographic and
                    linguistic features strongly support dating the inscription to six century BCE
                    Greece. The text is written boustrophedon, “plough-fashion,” when each line is
                    written in the reverse direction than the previous line. The letter forms and
                    lack of long-vowel discrimination are likewise distinctive to six century BCE.
                    As with many other funerary inscriptions, the epitaph is written in elegiac meter. A
                    signature of an inscriber names Phaedimus appears also in IG 1³ 1251, which is
                    dated to the same period. </p></div>
            
            <div type="apparatus">
            <p>line 1 ἔστε[σε], Alexander: ἔστε̂[κε̂]. line 3 &lt;λ>οφυρόμενο̣[ς. :], IG:
                    λοφυρόμενο[ς :] </p></div>
            

